Hello Mrs Smith,     Hayden was officially diagnosed with ADD yesterday and he started Concerta today. He has been struggling mightily and very burned out, but glad we figured out why. Apparently his therapist had suspicions years ago but she thinks the lack of academic rigor during the pandemic and then at his middle schools masked his issues. He was diagnosed by his psychiatrist but we are proceeding with full psychoeducational testing to be sure we aren't missing anything else. I will keep you updated.     Regarding midterms - I saw the schedule and I assume that kids with extended time go to a different location than kids without. Could you tell me where Hayden is supposed to go for his exams?     Thanks,  Megan Coursey     Sent from my iPhone

Hi Wolfpack,    I'm pleased to introduce the second Upper-Level Event of the summer -- the University Honors Program is heading back up to Virginia for a weekend in Williamsburg!    Screenshot 2024-05-19 at 1.27.52 PM.png    We'll have a Friday morning departure on June 7th and spend the afternoon exploring Colonial Williamsburg; we'll tour the Governor's Palace, Capitol, and Raleigh Tavern, and we'll visit trade shops, historic houses, and exhibition sites of Williamsburg's 18th century residents. Then we'll check into The Historic Powhatan, a residences resort with amenities including: indoor and outdoor pools, a sauna, tennis and racquetball courts, and a mini-golf course.    Saturday will be devoted to Water Country USA, Virginia's largest water park -- wave pools, lazy rivers, water coasters, live entertainment, and more! We'll call it quits when the park closes at 7pm and return to The Historic Powhatan for one more night before our departure on Sunday morning.     Including transportation, two nights at The Historic Powhatan, a half day at Colonial Williamsburg, and a full day at Water Country USA, this trip is available to UHP students at the low cost of $95. If this trip sounds like something you absolutely must add to your summer, please fill out this google form.    Thank you and have a great week!    --  Morgan Budzynski (she/her)  North Carolina State University  M.A. in Rhetoric and Composition C/O 2025  Administrative Assistant, University Honors Program

Good Afternoon,    You do not know me because I am not in one of your classes but I'm reaching out to you on behalf of one of your current students Owen Gabriel Gromyko.    I'm honestly not sure if he is in your class but i know he is in ECE 401 001 and is expecting to take an exam tomorrow at 8:30. If he is not one of your students, I apologize and hope you can redirect me accordingly.    I'm sure this is unusual, but I want to ask if it would even be possible for him to take his exam at least later in the day. He is sick with what I believe is the flu. I've been tending to him for a bit and he is having HORRIBLE muscle fatigue, sweats, pains, etc. All classic signs of the flu. I came over after he took an exam this morning and he told me how bad he was doing and that he had no pain meds for his headache. As his partner I came to help him. I've been on his bedside changing a cool cloth every few minutes because his temperature keeps causing it to heat up so quickly. Unfortunately he doesn't have a thermometer where he lives so I can't even send formal proof of his state.     I told him to try and reach out earlier but he assured me there was no way his exam could be considered for a later time. However, considering the increased emphasis on student health physically and mentally, I was hoping you would consider, if nothing else, allowing him to take the exam at a different hour. As I'm sure you can conclude, being this sick and worrying about an 8:30 am exam is not ideal for the healing process.    I do apologize for any inconvenience this may cause or disrespect this may come across as on my part, but I want what is best for him and I'm confident an exam tomorrow is not that, much less at 8:30 in the morning.    I did not copy him on this email because I did not want his hopes to get up; plus I know him and he'd probably try to tough it out instead of risking offending a professor. I hope you will consider what I am suggesting.    Best,  Chloe Coursey

Dear Patients,  We wanted to send out a reminder that our office hours during the next few weeks will be 9:00am to 1:00pm, for emergency patients only.  This includes the week of April 6th.  Due to the importance of social distancing, the government has relaxed many of the rules regarding telehealth visits, and we can now treat some patients via telephone calls or 2-way video conferences during our office hours of 9:00am-1:00pm.  This includes Medicare, Maryland Medicaid, and many commercial insurances (BCBS, Aetna, Cigna, United, to name a few).  If you call our office the doctor on staff will determine if you are a candidate for a telehealth visit.  If so, under the new guidelines, we will bill your insurance for the visit and are waiving your copay.  We hope that you and your loved ones are healthy and safe.  We encourage you to self quarantine, and to follow all CDC guidelines in regard to hand-washing and disinfecting.  Once again, we look forward to the time when we can return to our normal operations.  Sincerely,  Holly M. Gross, M.D.

Dear Client, This is a quick letter wishing you a happy 4th of July and mentioning a few things that you may have already noticed. The first is that as this severe drought continues lawns will turn browner if they are not irrigated. Please water if you can. As lawns turn brown they will first start to dry out and go dormant, but if the dry conditions continue the grass can easily go beyond dormancy and start to not just dry out but die out. As this occurs warm season grasses such as Bermuda grass that thrive in dry conditions will become much more noticeable. Although it is very common in many of our clients lawns, including mine, it is unfortunately like a cancer for grass and can slowly expand in time. Because it grows with aggressive rhizomes and tillers / vines it can easily become the dominant plant in some areas if nothing is done. It gets spread primarily by deer and bird poop droppings. They eat the grass and the seeds and it spreads from one lawn to another. The seeds can also be spread via mowing equipment. There is no way to selectively kill it without killing off the good grass as well. Another problem with drying grass is that the heavy wheels from lawn mowers can leave dead lines in the lawn (please see attached photo). There is still some room on our fall core aeration & seeding and mychorrizza schedule. Please let us know if you want to reserve your spot ane we will send you a quote for service. Soon we will begin our summer insecticide treatments. It targets ticks, fleas, spiders, ants, sod-webworms, crickets, chinch bugs, turfgrass weevils, bluegrass billbugs, cutworms, clover mites, and will reduce your mosquito population. We apply it to your grass and the beds around your house to create a barrier between the inside and the outside of your house. Stay safe and leave the fireworks to the professionals. Ha Ha!! Thanks, Rob, Greg, & Abe Chesapeake Lawn Science, Inc. 301-625-3232 www.chesapeakelawnscience.com

Dear Chloe Page Coursey,  I hope this message finds you well. I am writing on behalf of eSTEM, a dynamic organization dedicated to promoting equity and inclusion within the STEM fields. As we continue to expand our efforts to support minority and underrepresented students, we are excited to announce a unique mentorship opportunity and would love for you to be involved. By committing to only one hour a week, you can impact the life of an underrepresented STEM mentee.  About e-STEM: e-STEM is committed to bridging the gap for students from diverse backgrounds by providing comprehensive support through our 16-week Summer Bridge Program. This initiative is designed to prepare minority and underrepresented students for the upcoming school year by enhancing their STEM skills, fostering a growth mindset, and building a supportive community. This is a distance mentoring or e-mentoring program meaning that all contact will be facilitated through our proprietary software app STEM Squad.  e-Mentorship Opportunity: We are reaching out to seek passionate and dedicated mentors who can guide and inspire our students throughout this program. As a mentor, you will be crucial in shaping the future of aspiring young scientists, engineers, and mathematicians from minority and underrepresented backgrounds. Your involvement will include:  - Guiding Students: Provide one-on-one help to students navigate their academic and career paths. - Skill Development: Assist in developing critical thinking, problem-solving, and technical skills. - Support and Encouragement: Offer encouragement and support to boost students' confidence and motivation.  Benefits for e-Mentors:  - Stipend: Each mentor will receive a stipend of $650 as a token of appreciation for their commitment and effort. - Professional Development: Enhance your resume with valuable mentorship experience that demonstrates your leadership and commitment to equity in STEM. - Networking: Connect with like-minded professionals and expand your professional network. - Making a Difference: Contribute to a meaningful cause by empowering the next generation of STEM leaders.  Program Details:  - Duration: 16 weeks - Start Date: This summer, leading into the school year - Format: A blend of virtual and in-person activities, providing flexibility and accessibility for e-mentors and mentees.  Your organization's values align with our mission, and we would be thrilled to have your members join us as mentors. Your participation will not only enrich the lives of our students but also enhance the professional development of your team.  If you are interested in this opportunity, please follow this link: https://tinyurl.com/42k5kk8d Interested eSTEM Mentors must respond by June 17th for consideration for the program.  We look forward to your participation in our Organization!  Warm regards, Dr. Cameron D. Denson Principal Investigator e-STEM Project cddenson@ncsu.edu

Hello all,  After a great deal of deliberation, the OUR has made the difficult decision to suspend the OUR Research Assistant Program until we can secure a reliable increase in funding with which to sustain it.  The OUR RA program has been supported these past two years thanks to funding from the Chancellor's Greatest Needs Fund and by a matching gift from DASA.  While we have not yet secured a more permanent source of funding for the OUR RA program, we remain dedicated to doing so.  The rapid rise in applications during the past two years of implementation underscores student interest in conducting undergraduate research and the need for financial support in order to do so.  We remain committed to making research more accessible.  The OUR spends more than 80% of its annual budget directly on supporting student researchers with the remaining amount going towards office upkeep and indirect support of students such as the costs associated with hosting our annual symposia.  We'd like to take a moment to thank our colleagues from the Data Science Academy and University Honors for lending their financial support to the OUR RA program which allowed us to support even more students and to keep it going longer.  We appreciate your generosity.  Moving forward, the OUR will continue to fund: Project Supply Grants (which have a lower operating budget than the OUR RA's), the Federal Work Study Research Assistant Program, and Travel Grants.  We know that the suspension of the OUR RA Program is disappointing.  As we work to bring this program back, please take advantage of the scholarships and funding opportunities we share via our website.  Students are invited to meet with staff at the OUR and/or the University Fellowships Office for guidance on applications.  Thank you in advance for your understanding, -Office of Undergraduate Research (OUR)  Join the OUR Google Group NC State University Campus Box 7576 DH Hill Jr. Library, Suite 2425 Raleigh, NC 27695-7576 919-513-0095 - main office number undergraduate-research@ncsu.edu
